pouch boundary-line patch 0007 - the POSIX signal layer over Thylacine notes.

Phase 6 sub-chunk 13b (pouch-signals, pouch side). Retargets musl's
src/signal/ from Linux's SYS_rt_sigaction / SYS_rt_sigprocmask /
SYS_tkill / SYS_kill / SYS_rt_sigreturn onto the five kernel note
syscalls landed at sub-chunk 13a (P6-pouch-signals-impl; kernel
substrate audited across 4 rounds, 42 findings dispositioned):

  SYS_note_open = 44   open the per-Proc note Spoor (devnotes fd)
  SYS_notify    = 45   register the async-handler bootstrap (handler_va)
  SYS_noted     = 46   return from a running handler (NCONT / NDFLT)
  SYS_postnote  = 47   post a note to another Proc (pid=0 = self-post)
  SYS_note_mask = 48   set per-Thread mask (NOTE_BIT_INTERRUPT/KILL/PIPE/CHILD_EXIT)

Nine files. The boundary-line stays at musl's src/signal/ + src/thread/
pthread_sigmask + src/internal/syscall.h.in. The portable upper half
(signal.h, sigsetops, sigemptyset etc.) is unchanged.

  PAIRED WITH a one-line kernel change (in the same commit, not in this
  patch file): sys_postnote_handler in kernel/syscall.c accepts pid_raw
  == 0 as the self-post sentinel. raise() depends on this — pouch has
  no userspace getpid path at v1.0 and the kernel post-gate compares
  target_pid against the caller's p->pid. The sentinel mirrors the
  existing SYS_WALK_OPEN_FROM_ROOT discipline (a magic value reserved
  on the syscall ABI).

  arch/aarch64/bits/syscall.h.in   Appends five Thylacine note extension
      numbers - __NR_note_open 44, __NR_notify 45, __NR_noted 46,
      __NR_postnote 47, __NR_note_mask 48 - so musl's sed pass
      generates the SYS_note_open / SYS_notify / SYS_noted /
      SYS_postnote / SYS_note_mask aliases the replacement files use.
      After a musl re-vendor, extend 0001's awk filter:
          m["note_open"]="44"; m["notify"]="45";
          m["noted"]="46"; m["postnote"]="47"; m["note_mask"]="48";

  src/internal/_pouch_signal.h     New header. The pouch signal layer's
      public-to-libc-but-private-to-pouch API: __pouch_sigtab[NSIG] (the
      per-Proc sigaction table; sigaction()'s storage); __pouch_note_-
      mask_shadow (__thread TLS — pouch's shadow of the kernel note
      mask, sole writer); __pouch_sig_to_note() (signum -> canonical
      note name); __pouch_note_handler (the bootstrap registered via
      SYS_NOTIFY); __pouch_note_name_eq (bounded 16-byte compare —
      matches the kernel's user-stack push); __pouch_sigset_to_note /
      __pouch_note_to_sigset (sigset_t <-> NOTE_BIT_* marshalling).

      The v1.0 supported set (POUCH-DESIGN.md section 6.4):
          SIGINT  -> "interrupt"    catchable; default = exits("interrupt")
          SIGTERM -> "interrupt"    catchable; SHARED with SIGINT at v1.0
          SIGPIPE -> "pipe"         catchable; pouch masks at startup
          SIGCHLD -> "child_exit"   catchable; default = ignore
          SIGKILL -> "kill"         non-catchable; sigaction() returns EINVAL
      All other signums return EINVAL at sigaction() time. SIGTERM
      shares the "interrupt" note with SIGINT at v1.0; the dispatcher
      prefers SIGINT's handler if installed, falls back to SIGTERM.

  src/signal/_pouch_signal.c       New source. The bootstrap async-
      handler implementation:

      __pouch_note_handler(name, arg)  Plan-9-style ABI: x0 = user-stack
          pointer to 16-byte note name; x1 = note arg. Looks up the
          signum from the name, dispatches by SIG_DFL / SIG_IGN / user
          handler. Ends with SYS_NOTED(NCONT) on user-handler / SIG_IGN
          return. SIG_DFL branch issues SYS_NOTED(NDFLT) for terminating
          signals; F2 audit close adds an NCONT-fallback on NDFLT
          refusal — a multi-thread Proc's kernel-side R3-F2 gate refuses
          NDFLT (cross-thread shootdown is v1.x), without the fallback
          the receiving Thread would drop into for(;;), wedging
          permanently. NEVER returns normally.

      __pouch_signal_init  Constructor (.init_array entry). Runs once
          at process startup on the main thread, BEFORE main(). Sets
          NOTE_BIT_PIPE in the kernel mask (SIGPIPE default-mask per
          POUCH-DESIGN section 6.4 [RESOLVED 6.4]); registers
          __pouch_note_handler via SYS_NOTIFY.

      __pouch_note_name_eq  Bounded 16-byte name compare. The kernel
          pushes exactly POUCH_NOTE_NAME_MAX (= NOTE_NAME_MAX = 16)
          bytes onto the user stack, NUL-padded; the literal side of
          every v1.0 supported name is < 16 chars + NUL.

  src/signal/sigaction.c           Full rewrite. Validates signum
      (refuses everything outside {SIGINT, SIGTERM, SIGPIPE, SIGCHLD}
      with EINVAL — this implicitly catches SIGKILL / SIGSTOP);
      F11 audit close rejects sa_handler == SIG_ERR (POSIX-invalid;
      otherwise the bootstrap would call h(SIGINT) at address -1);
      records/swaps the user sigaction into __pouch_sigtab[sig];
      adjusts the kernel mask on SIGPIPE handler install/uninstall
      (a real handler clears NOTE_BIT_PIPE so the note delivers).
      Loses musl's SIGABRT/__abort_lock interlock. NOTE on abort():
      musl's abort.c reaches a_crash() (a deliberate NULL deref)
      which lands as EL0 fault. At v1.0 the kernel's FAULT_UNHANDLED_-
      USER policy extincts on EL0 faults from any pouch program —
      so abort() manifests as kernel extinction rather than clean
      process termination. This is a PRE-EXISTING v1.0 limitation
      (NOT introduced by sub-chunk 13b) and is documented in
      docs/reference/83-pouch-signals.md as a v1.x extension.

  src/signal/raise.c               Full rewrite. Translates sig ->
      note name via __pouch_sig_to_note, calls syscall(SYS_postnote,
      0L, name, name_len). The kernel's pid=0 self-post sentinel
      routes the note to the caller's Proc. The handler runs at the
      EL0-return tail of the SYS_POSTNOTE itself: raise() returns
      after the handler executes.

  src/signal/kill.c                Full rewrite. Same shape as raise;
      passes the user-supplied pid. The kernel's POSTNOTE gate
      (parent-of-target OR self-post) governs cross-Proc posts;
      pouch is unchanged by it.

  src/signal/block.c               Full rewrite. __block_all_sigs /
      __block_app_sigs / __restore_sigs map onto SYS_NOTE_MASK. The
      sigset_t shape is preserved (callers stash to on-stack
      storage); marshalling is bounded (4 supported bits).

  src/signal/aarch64/restore.s     Rewrite. The asm restorer stubs
      __restore / __restore_rt are called only via the legacy Linux
      sa_restorer mechanism, which pouch's sigaction.c no longer
      installs — the symbols become dead static-archive references
      at v1.0. As defense-in-depth, the stubs now call SYS_NOTED
      (#46) NCONT (#0) instead of SYS_rt_sigreturn (#139); any
      indirect call lands on the correct kernel handler rather than
      the 0xFFFF unimplemented-syscall sentinel. F10 audit close
      adds a `b .` (infinite branch-to-self) after the SVC so that
      a SYS_NOTED return on -1 (out-of-handler call; should never
      happen but defense-in-depth) traps rather than falls off the
      end of __restore_rt into adjacent .text bytes.

  src/thread/pthread_sigmask.c     Full rewrite. Marshals POSIX
      sigset_t <-> NOTE_BIT_* via the _pouch_signal helpers; reads
      __pouch_note_mask_shadow for the SIG_BLOCK / SIG_UNBLOCK
      read-modify-write paths (pouch is the sole writer; shadow stays
      in sync with the kernel's per-Thread note_mask). sigprocmask()
      delegates here (UNCHANGED — already a thin wrapper).

Files NOT modified despite referencing Linux signal syscall numbers
(all hit the 0xFFFF sentinel at runtime via the unchanged 0001 awk
mapping → -ENOSYS; documented v1.0 limitations):

  src/signal/sigsetjmp_tail.c      SYS_rt_sigprocmask; sigsetjmp's
